04375nam a22005535i 9780887558597DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808875585977 a10.1515/97808875585972doi  a(DE-B1597)664609  a(OCoLC)1130756910  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA 4aNX513.A1bR43 2020eb 7aLIT0040802bisacsh04a700.9712231 aRedekop, Magdalene, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaking Believe :bQuestions About Mennonites and Art /cMagdalene Redekop. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tApologia -- tOn Beginnings -- tReframing Old Questions -- tMaking Believe -- tUs and Them -- tClowning with Low German -- tResisting Nostalgia -- tWitnessing a New Phenomenon -- tLocation, Dislocation -- tMelos and Logos -- tClowning With Masks -- tIconoclash -- tOn Endings -- tAcknowledgements -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMaking Believe responds to a remarkable flowering of art by Mennonites in Canada. After the publication of his first novel in 1962, Rudy Wiebe was the only identifiable Mennonite literary writer in the country. Beginning in the 1970s, the numbers grew rapidly and now include writers Patrick Friesen, Sandra Birdsell, Di Brandt, Sarah Klassen, Armin Wiebe, David Bergen, Miriam Toews, Carrie Snyder, Casey Plett, and many more. A similar renaissance is evident in the visual arts (including artists Gathie Falk, Wanda Koop, and Aganetha Dyck) and in music (including composers Randolph Peters, Carol Ann Weaver, and Stephanie Martin). Confronted with an embarrassment of riches that resist survey, Magdalene Redekop opts for the use of case studies to raise questions about Mennonites and art. Part criticism, part memoir, Making Believe argues that there is no such thing as Mennonite art. At the same time, her close engagement with individual works of art paradoxically leads Redekop to identify a Mennonite sensibility at play in the space where artists from many cultures interact. Constant questioning and commitment to community are part of the Mennonite dissenting tradition. Although these values come up against the legacy of radical Anabaptist hostility to art, Redekop argues that the Early Modern roots of a contemporary crisis of representation are shared by all artists. Making Believe posits a Spielraum or play space in which all artists are dissembling tricksters, but differences in how we play are inflected by where we come from. The close readings in this book insist on respect for difference at the same time as they invite readers to find common ground while making believe across cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian literaturexMennonite authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aMennonite artzCanada. 0aMennoniteszCanada. 0aMusiczCanadaxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020z978311127473740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755859740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887558597423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887558597/original  a978-3-11-127253-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-127473-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles